<div id="crucendo-features" class="panel panel-help">
  <div class="panel-heading">
    <div class="panel-title">Description of Crucendo’s features</div>
  </div>
  <div class="panel-body">
    <h3>Dashboard</h3>
    <p>The Dashboard is like a home to all of your activities. Want to think 
    about what you’ve improved today? How about what you’d like to improve in 
    the future? Would you like to see your history, or impress yourself? This is
    the place to do all of that, and more.</p>
    <h3>Begin a new Crucendo</h3>
    <p>Now we’re talking. This is the exciting stuff, and the reason that you’re
    here. Clicking on ‘Begin a new Crucendo’ begins a new Crucendo, and thus 
    also starts the process of developing yourself. Every time that you click 
    the magical ‘Begin a new Crucendo’ button, you can spend time being 
    retrospective and thinking about the day that was. To be serious for a 
    moment, this is the heart of Crucendo and what will give you the most 
    personal development.</p>
    <h3>Haves</h3>
    <p>We’re asking for some recent accomplishments, or to write some skills 
    that you have improved on. E.g. If you feel like you got better at listening
    today, you could write “listening”. Doing this will add listening to your 
    list of areas that you have improved recently.</p>
    <h3>Wants</h3>
    <p>We’re looking for you to share something about the future. E.g. If you 
    want to improve your question asking skills, you could write something like 
    “improve the quality of questions I ask”. This will then feature in your 
    list of areas, that you want to develop in the future.</p>
    <h3>Accomplishments</h3>
    <p>Every great achiever has a list of their past accomplishments, and 
    Crucendo is no different. Jump in to the Accomplishments section, and you 
    can view all of your past Crucendos along with anything else you’ve 
    completed. You can run reports and gather statistical information, so that 
    you can learn more about your awesome efforts.</p>
    <h3>Subscriptions</h3>
    <p>In every Crucendo you get to challenge and encourage yourself, with a 
    series of questions. The Subscriptions section of Crucendo, allows you the 
    ability to adjust what type of questions you get. This gives you the option 
    to tailor your experience in Crucendo, and it also allows you the ability 
    to focus the questions you get asked around specific areas of your life.</p>
    <h3>Profile</h3>
    <p>A few basics about yourself. Nothing too invasive, we’re just keen on 
    knowing a little about you, and all of the wonderful people using Crucendo. 
    You can also see where you have Crucendo sessions open, and end them as 
    needed. You can also change your email address, but keep in mind that you 
    will need access to your old and new email addresses to do so.</p>
    <h3>Help</h3>
    <p>Ummm, you’re here already. It’s… helpful.</p>
    <h3>Logout</h3>
    <p>Finished conquering the world for the day? That’s cool, it’s time to 
    logout, if you’re one of those logout people. If you’re not one of those 
    logout people, you can just stay logged in. Keep in mind, if you share a 
    computer, tablet, etc, you should logout to protect your privacy.</p>
    <h3>Completed Wants</h3>
    <p>A feature of the dash, and a visual representation of how many ‘wants’ 
    you have completed. It also features a sub-achievement, which is “total 
    wants” and an indicator of the total goals set. Both numbers should 
    hopefully be forever climbing, as they reflect all-time numbers rather 
    than a specific period of time.</p>
    <h3>Total Improvements</h3>
    <p>Every time that you have improved something in your list, you should 
    click it to indicate just that. So each time that you say you’ve improved 
    something, it adds another improvement to the list of total improvements. 
    This feature of the dash will also display the total number of improvements 
    you’ve made, in the last seven days, like a rolling number of successes.</p>
    <h3>Consecutive Days</h3>
    <p>With anything designed to help with personal development, it’s important 
    to keep challenging yourself to always do better/more. Consecutive Days is 
    designed to motivate you to complete a Crucendo each day, and to keep the 
    number of consecutive days completing a Crucendo climbing. The Consecutive 
    Days counter is not only for what you’ve currently achieved, but also to 
    display your all-time best number of consecutive days.</p>
  </div>
